data.content:
## What happened

In C# 14, new **`Span<T>` / `ReadOnlySpan<T>` overload resolution rules** cause `array.Contains(num)` to bind to `MemoryExtensions.Contains` (span-based) instead of `Enumerable.Contains` (IEnumerable-based). Expression trees **cannot represent span-based calls**, so this throws at runtime.

## How to fix it

Cast the array to `IEnumerable<int>`, use `.AsEnumerable()`, or call `Enumerable.Contains` explicitly:

```csharp
// Option 1: .AsEnumerable()
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => array.AsEnumerable().Contains(num);

// Option 2: Explicit static call
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);
```

This forces the compiler to pick the `IEnumerable<T>` overload, which is representable in expression trees. The same issue affects `.Reverse()` on arrays — use `Enumerable.Reverse(arr)` instead.
